
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Problematizing Fit and Survival: Transforming the Law of Requisite Variety Through Complexity Misalignment
AU  - Poulis, Konstantinos
AU  - Poulis, Efthimios
Y1  - 2015/07/17
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2016/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2014.0073
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2014.0073
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 503
EP  - 527
VL  - 41
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The law of requisite variety is widely employed in management theorizing and is linked with core strategy themes such as contingency and fit. We reflect upon requisite variety as an archetypal borrowed concept. We contrast its premises with insights from the institutional literature and commitment literature, draw propositions that set boundaries to its applicability, and review the ramifications of what we call ?complexity misalignment.? In this way we contradict foundational assumptions of the law, problematize adaptation- and survival-centric views of strategizing, and theorize the role of human agency in variously complex regimes.
AB  - The law of requisite variety is widely employed in management theorizing and is linked with core strategy themes such as contingency and fit. We reflect upon requisite variety as an archetypal borrowed concept. We contrast its premises with insights from the institutional literature and commitment literature, draw propositions that set boundaries to its applicability, and review the ramifications of what we call ?complexity misalignment.? In this way we contradict foundational assumptions of the law, problematize adaptation- and survival-centric views of strategizing, and theorize the role of human agency in variously complex regimes.
